The specific spring constants were chosen to produce relatively low natural frequencies and correspondingly large displacements of the structure while at the same time limiting estimated static deflection to 5% of strut length. To determine this, a single strut was modeled as being connected to four linear springs at each end, equally spaced around the radius, each at a \documentclass{aastex}\usepackage{amsbsy}\usepackage{amsfonts}\usepackage{amssymb}\usepackage{bm}\usepackage{mathrsfs}\usepackage{pifont}\usepackage{stmaryrd}\usepackage{textcomp}\usepackage{portland, xspace}\usepackage{amsmath, amsxtra}\usepackage{upgreek}\pagestyle{empty}\DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}\begin{document}
$${45^ \circ }$$
\end{document} angle. Limiting static deflection to 5% of strut length results in a spring constant value of 0.209 N/cm. Subsequently, the entire six-bar structure was modeled by assuming that one strut was to be anchored in place and then using matrix structural analysis to determine the natural frequencies. The vibrational motor was then chosen that was capable of generating sufficient centrifugal force at a suitable range of frequencies. Details of the modeling and design are provided in Ref.34

Each policy is defined by three pulse width modulation (PWM) values that determine the input voltage of the three vibrating motors \documentclass{aastex}\usepackage{amsbsy}\usepackage{amsfonts}\usepackage{amssymb}\usepackage{bm}\usepackage{mathrsfs}\usepackage{pifont}\usepackage{stmaryrd}\usepackage{textcomp}\usepackage{portland, xspace}\usepackage{amsmath, amsxtra}\usepackage{upgreek}\pagestyle{empty}\DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}\begin{document}
$$( \chi = [ {v_1} , {v_2} , {v_3} ] )$$
\end{document}, which can take values between 0 (full speed, backward) and 1 (full speed, forward); 0.5 corresponds to a speed of 0, that is, to no movement.

We use the profile plots to depict the search space and the prior used by the learning algorithm (Fig. 2). For each pair of dimensions, we discretize the motor speeds into 25 bins. For each bin, we compute \documentclass{aastex}\usepackage{amsbsy}\usepackage{amsfonts}\usepackage{amssymb}\usepackage{bm}\usepackage{mathrsfs}\usepackage{pifont}\usepackage{stmaryrd}\usepackage{textcomp}\usepackage{portland, xspace}\usepackage{amsmath, amsxtra}\usepackage{upgreek}\pagestyle{empty}\DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}\begin{document}
$${p_{profile}} ( {v_1} , \,{v_2} ) = \mathop { \max } \nolimits_{{v_3}} p ( {v_1} , \,{v_2} , \,{v_3} )$$
\end{document}, where \documentclass{aastex}\usepackage{amsbsy}\usepackage{amsfonts}\usepackage{amssymb}\usepackage{bm}\usepackage{mathrsfs}\usepackage{pifont}\usepackage{stmaryrd}\usepackage{textcomp}\usepackage{portland, xspace}\usepackage{amsmath, amsxtra}\usepackage{upgreek}\pagestyle{empty}\DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}\begin{document}
$$p ( {v_1} , \,{v_2} , \,{v_3} )$$
\end{document} is the performance of the robot for motor speeds \documentclass{aastex}\usepackage{amsbsy}\usepackage{amsfonts}\usepackage{amssymb}\usepackage{bm}\usepackage{mathrsfs}\usepackage{pifont}\usepackage{stmaryrd}\usepackage{textcomp}\usepackage{portland, xspace}\usepackage{amsmath, amsxtra}\usepackage{upgreek}\pagestyle{empty}\DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}\begin{document}
$${v_1} , {v_2} , {v_3}$$
\end{document} and \documentclass{aastex}\usepackage{amsbsy}\usepackage{amsfonts}\usepackage{amssymb}\usepackage{bm}\usepackage{mathrsfs}\usepackage{pifont}\usepackage{stmaryrd}\usepackage{textcomp}\usepackage{portland, xspace}\usepackage{amsmath, amsxtra}\usepackage{upgreek}\pagestyle{empty}\DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}\begin{document}
$${p_{profile}} ( {v_1} , {v_2} )$$
\end{document} is the performance reported in the profile. To get comprehensive pictures, we need three plots: \documentclass{aastex}\usepackage{amsbsy}\usepackage{amsfonts}\usepackage{amssymb}\usepackage{bm}\usepackage{mathrsfs}\usepackage{pifont}\usepackage{stmaryrd}\usepackage{textcomp}\usepackage{portland, xspace}\usepackage{amsmath, amsxtra}\usepackage{upgreek}\pagestyle{empty}\DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}\begin{document}
$${p_{profile}} ( {v_1} , \,{v_2} )$$
\end{document}, \documentclass{aastex}\usepackage{amsbsy}\usepackage{amsfonts}\usepackage{amssymb}\usepackage{bm}\usepackage{mathrsfs}\usepackage{pifont}\usepackage{stmaryrd}\usepackage{textcomp}\usepackage{portland, xspace}\usepackage{amsmath, amsxtra}\usepackage{upgreek}\pagestyle{empty}\DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}\begin{document}
$${p_{profile}} ( {v_1} , \,{v_3} )$$
\end{document}, and \documentclass{aastex}\usepackage{amsbsy}\usepackage{amsfonts}\usepackage{amssymb}\usepackage{bm}\usepackage{mathrsfs}\usepackage{pifont}\usepackage{stmaryrd}\usepackage{textcomp}\usepackage{portland, xspace}\usepackage{amsmath, amsxtra}\usepackage{upgreek}\pagestyle{empty}\DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}\begin{document}
$${p_{profile}} ( {v_2} , \,{v_3} )$$
\end{document}.

Here a Gaussian process models the objective function,38 which is a common choice for Bayesian optimization.36,37,46–48 For an unknown cost function f, a Gaussian process defines the probability distribution of the possible values \documentclass{aastex}\usepackage{amsbsy}\usepackage{amsfonts}\usepackage{amssymb}\usepackage{bm}\usepackage{mathrsfs}\usepackage{pifont}\usepackage{stmaryrd}\usepackage{textcomp}\usepackage{portland, xspace}\usepackage{amsmath, amsxtra}\usepackage{upgreek}\pagestyle{empty}\DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}\begin{document}
$$f ( { \bf{x}} )$$
\end{document} for each point x. These probability distributions are Gaussian, and are, therefore, defined by a mean (\documentclass{aastex}\usepackage{amsbsy}\usepackage{amsfonts}\usepackage{amssymb}\usepackage{bm}\usepackage{mathrsfs}\usepackage{pifont}\usepackage{stmaryrd}\usepackage{textcomp}\usepackage{portland, xspace}\usepackage{amsmath, amsxtra}\usepackage{upgreek}\pagestyle{empty}\DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}\begin{document}
$$\mu$$
\end{document}) and a variance \documentclass{aastex}\usepackage{amsbsy}\usepackage{amsfonts}\usepackage{amssymb}\usepackage{bm}\usepackage{mathrsfs}\usepackage{pifont}\usepackage{stmaryrd}\usepackage{textcomp}\usepackage{portland, xspace}\usepackage{amsmath, amsxtra}\usepackage{upgreek}\pagestyle{empty}\DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}\begin{document}
$$( { \sigma ^2} )$$
\end{document}. However, \documentclass{aastex}\usepackage{amsbsy}\usepackage{amsfonts}\usepackage{amssymb}\usepackage{bm}\usepackage{mathrsfs}\usepackage{pifont}\usepackage{stmaryrd}\usepackage{textcomp}\usepackage{portland, xspace}\usepackage{amsmath, amsxtra}\usepackage{upgreek}\pagestyle{empty}\DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}\begin{document}
$$\mu$$
\end{document} and \documentclass{aastex}\usepackage{amsbsy}\usepackage{amsfonts}\usepackage{amssymb}\usepackage{bm}\usepackage{mathrsfs}\usepackage{pifont}\usepackage{stmaryrd}\usepackage{textcomp}\usepackage{portland, xspace}\usepackage{amsmath, amsxtra}\usepackage{upgreek}\pagestyle{empty}\DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}\begin{document}
$${ \sigma ^2}$$
\end{document} can be different for each x; a Gaussian process, therefore, defines a probability distribution over functions:
\documentclass{aastex}\usepackage{amsbsy}\usepackage{amsfonts}\usepackage{amssymb}\usepackage{bm}\usepackage{mathrsfs}\usepackage{pifont}\usepackage{stmaryrd}\usepackage{textcomp}\usepackage{portland, xspace}\usepackage{amsmath, amsxtra}\usepackage{upgreek}\pagestyle{empty}\DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}\begin{document}
\begin{align*}
P(f({{\textbf{x}}} ) \vert {{\textbf{x}}} ) = {\mathcal{N}} ( \mu
( { {\textbf{x}}} ) , { \sigma ^2} ( { {\textbf{x}}} ) ) , \tag{1}
\end{align*}
\end{document}

where \documentclass{aastex}\usepackage{amsbsy}\usepackage{amsfonts}\usepackage{amssymb}\usepackage{bm}\usepackage{mathrsfs}\usepackage{pifont}\usepackage{stmaryrd}\usepackage{textcomp}\usepackage{portland, xspace}\usepackage{amsmath, amsxtra}\usepackage{upgreek}\pagestyle{empty}\DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}\begin{document}
$${\mathcal{N}}$$
\end{document} denotes the standard normal distribution.

At iteration t, if the performance \documentclass{aastex}\usepackage{amsbsy}\usepackage{amsfonts}\usepackage{amssymb}\usepackage{bm}\usepackage{mathrsfs}\usepackage{pifont}\usepackage{stmaryrd}\usepackage{textcomp}\usepackage{portland, xspace}\usepackage{amsmath, amsxtra}\usepackage{upgreek}\pagestyle{empty}\DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}\begin{document}
$$[ {P_1} , \cdots , {P_t} ] = {{ \bf{P}}_{1:t}}$$
\end{document} of the points \documentclass{aastex}\usepackage{amsbsy}\usepackage{amsfonts}\usepackage{amssymb}\usepackage{bm}\usepackage{mathrsfs}\usepackage{pifont}\usepackage{stmaryrd}\usepackage{textcomp}\usepackage{portland, xspace}\usepackage{amsmath, amsxtra}\usepackage{upgreek}\pagestyle{empty}\DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}\begin{document}
$$[ { \chi _1} , \cdots , { \chi _{ \bf{t}}} ] = { \chi _{1:t}}$$
\end{document} has already been evaluated, then \documentclass{aastex}\usepackage{amsbsy}\usepackage{amsfonts}\usepackage{amssymb}\usepackage{bm}\usepackage{mathrsfs}\usepackage{pifont}\usepackage{stmaryrd}\usepackage{textcomp}\usepackage{portland, xspace}\usepackage{amsmath, amsxtra}\usepackage{upgreek}\pagestyle{empty}\DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}\begin{document}
$${ \mu _t} ( { \bf{x}} )$$
\end{document} and \documentclass{aastex}\usepackage{amsbsy}\usepackage{amsfonts}\usepackage{amssymb}\usepackage{bm}\usepackage{mathrsfs}\usepackage{pifont}\usepackage{stmaryrd}\usepackage{textcomp}\usepackage{portland, xspace}\usepackage{amsmath, amsxtra}\usepackage{upgreek}\pagestyle{empty}\DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}\begin{document}
$$\sigma _t^2 ( { \bf{x}} )$$
\end{document} are fitted as follows38:
\documentclass{aastex}\usepackage{amsbsy}\usepackage{amsfonts}\usepackage{amssymb}\usepackage{bm}\usepackage{mathrsfs}\usepackage{pifont}\usepackage{stmaryrd}\usepackage{textcomp}\usepackage{portland, xspace}\usepackage{amsmath, amsxtra}\usepackage{upgreek}\pagestyle{empty}\DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}\begin{document}
\begin{align*}
\begin{matrix} { \begin{matrix} {{ \mu _t} ( { \bf{x}} ) = {{ \bf{k}}^ \texttt{T} }{{ \bf{K}}^{ - 1}}{{ \bf{P}}_{1:t}}} \hfill \\ { \sigma _t^2 ( { \bf{x}} ) = k ( { \bf{x}} , \,{ \bf{x}} ) + \sigma _{noise}^2 - {{ \bf{k}}^ \texttt{T} }{{ \bf{K}}^{ - 1}}{ \bf{k}} , } \hfill \\ {where} \hfill \\ {{ \bf{K}} = \left[ { \begin{matrix} {k ( { \chi _1} , \,{ \chi _1} ) } & \cdots & {k ( { \chi _1} , \,{ \chi _t} ) } \\ \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\ {k ( { \chi _t} , \,{ \chi _1} ) } & \cdots & {k ( { \chi _t} , \,{ \chi _t} ) } \\ \end{matrix} } \right] + \sigma _{noise}^2I} \hfill \\ {{ \bf{k}} = \left[ { \begin{matrix} {k ( { \bf{x}} , \,{ \chi _1} ) } & {k ( { \bf{x}} , \,{ \chi _2} ) } & \cdots & {k ( { \bf{x}} , \,{ \chi _t} ) } \\ \end{matrix} } \right] .} \hfill \\ \end{matrix} } \\ \end{matrix} \tag{2}
\end{align*}
\end{document}

Matrix K is called the covariance matrix. It is based on a kernel function
\documentclass{aastex}\usepackage{amsbsy}\usepackage{amsfonts}\usepackage{amssymb}\usepackage{bm}\usepackage{mathrsfs}\usepackage{pifont}\usepackage{stmaryrd}\usepackage{textcomp}\usepackage{portland, xspace}\usepackage{amsmath, amsxtra}\usepackage{upgreek}\pagestyle{empty}\DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}\begin{document}
$$k ( {{ \bf{x}}_{ \bf{1}}} , {{ \bf{x}}_{ \bf{2}}} )$$
\end{document} that defines how samples influence each other. Kernel functions are classically variants of the Euclidean distance. Here we use the exponential kernel12,37,38,48:
\documentclass{aastex}\usepackage{amsbsy}\usepackage{amsfonts}\usepackage{amssymb}\usepackage{bm}\usepackage{mathrsfs}\usepackage{pifont}\usepackage{stmaryrd}\usepackage{textcomp}\usepackage{portland, xspace}\usepackage{amsmath, amsxtra}\usepackage{upgreek}\pagestyle{empty}\DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}\begin{document}
\begin{align*}
k ( { { \bf { x } } _ { \bf { 1 } } } , \, { { \bf { x } } _ { \bf { 2 } } } ) = \exp \left( { - \frac { 1 }  { { { \beta ^2 } } } \vert \vert { { \bf { x } } _ { \bf { 1 } } } - { { \bf { x } } _ { \bf { 2 } } } { { \vert \vert } ^2 } } \right) , \tag { 3 } 
\end{align*}
\end{document}

because this is the most common kernel in Bayesian optimization and we did not see any reason to choose a different one.37,48 We fixed \documentclass{aastex}\usepackage{amsbsy}\usepackage{amsfonts}\usepackage{amssymb}\usepackage{bm}\usepackage{mathrsfs}\usepackage{pifont}\usepackage{stmaryrd}\usepackage{textcomp}\usepackage{portland, xspace}\usepackage{amsmath, amsxtra}\usepackage{upgreek}\pagestyle{empty}\DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}\begin{document}
$$\beta$$
\end{document} to \documentclass{aastex}\usepackage{amsbsy}\usepackage{amsfonts}\usepackage{amssymb}\usepackage{bm}\usepackage{mathrsfs}\usepackage{pifont}\usepackage{stmaryrd}\usepackage{textcomp}\usepackage{portland, xspace}\usepackage{amsmath, amsxtra}\usepackage{upgreek}\pagestyle{empty}\DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}\begin{document}
$$0.15$$
\end{document}.

An interesting feature of Gaussian processes is that they can easily incorporate a prior \documentclass{aastex}\usepackage{amsbsy}\usepackage{amsfonts}\usepackage{amssymb}\usepackage{bm}\usepackage{mathrsfs}\usepackage{pifont}\usepackage{stmaryrd}\usepackage{textcomp}\usepackage{portland, xspace}\usepackage{amsmath, amsxtra}\usepackage{upgreek}\pagestyle{empty}\DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}\begin{document}
$${ \mu _p} ( { \bf{x}} )$$
\end{document} for the mean function, which helps to guide the optimization process to zones that are known to be promising:
\documentclass{aastex}\usepackage{amsbsy}\usepackage{amsfonts}\usepackage{amssymb}\usepackage{bm}\usepackage{mathrsfs}\usepackage{pifont}\usepackage{stmaryrd}\usepackage{textcomp}\usepackage{portland, xspace}\usepackage{amsmath, amsxtra}\usepackage{upgreek}\pagestyle{empty}\DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}\begin{document}
\begin{align*}
{ \mu _t} ( { \bf{x}} ) = { \mu _p} ( { \bf{x}} ) + {{ \bf{k}}^ \texttt{T} }{{ \bf{K}}^{ - 1}} ( {{ \bf{P}}_{1:t}} - { \mu _p} ( { \chi _{1:t}} ) ) .. \tag{4}
\end{align*}
\end{document}

To select the next \documentclass{aastex}\usepackage{amsbsy}\usepackage{amsfonts}\usepackage{amssymb}\usepackage{bm}\usepackage{mathrsfs}\usepackage{pifont}\usepackage{stmaryrd}\usepackage{textcomp}\usepackage{portland, xspace}\usepackage{amsmath, amsxtra}\usepackage{upgreek}\pagestyle{empty}\DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}\begin{document}
$$\chi$$
\end{document} to test (\documentclass{aastex}\usepackage{amsbsy}\usepackage{amsfonts}\usepackage{amssymb}\usepackage{bm}\usepackage{mathrsfs}\usepackage{pifont}\usepackage{stmaryrd}\usepackage{textcomp}\usepackage{portland, xspace}\usepackage{amsmath, amsxtra}\usepackage{upgreek}\pagestyle{empty}\DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}\begin{document}
$${ \chi _{t + 1}}$$
\end{document}), Bayesian optimization maximizes an acquisition function, a function that reflects the need to balance exploration—improving the model in the less known parts of the search space—and exploitation—favoring parts that the model predicts as promising. Numerous acquisition functions have been proposed (e.g., probability of improvement, the expected improvement, or the upper confidence bound (UCB)37,47,48); we chose UCB because it provided the best results in several previous studies47,48 and because of its simplicity. The equation for UCB is
\documentclass{aastex}\usepackage{amsbsy}\usepackage{amsfonts}\usepackage{amssymb}\usepackage{bm}\usepackage{mathrsfs}\usepackage{pifont}\usepackage{stmaryrd}\usepackage{textcomp}\usepackage{portland, xspace}\usepackage{amsmath, amsxtra}\usepackage{upgreek}\pagestyle{empty}\DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}\begin{document}
\begin{align*}
{ \chi _{t + 1}} = \mathop { \arg \max } \limits_x ( { \mu _t} ( { \bf{x}} ) + \kappa { \sigma _t} ( { \bf{x}} ) ) , \tag{5}
\end{align*}
\end{document}

where \documentclass{aastex}\usepackage{amsbsy}\usepackage{amsfonts}\usepackage{amssymb}\usepackage{bm}\usepackage{mathrsfs}\usepackage{pifont}\usepackage{stmaryrd}\usepackage{textcomp}\usepackage{portland, xspace}\usepackage{amsmath, amsxtra}\usepackage{upgreek}\pagestyle{empty}\DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}\begin{document}
$$\kappa$$
\end{document} is a user-defined parameter that tunes the tradeoff between exploration and exploitation. We chose \documentclass{aastex}\usepackage{amsbsy}\usepackage{amsfonts}\usepackage{amssymb}\usepackage{bm}\usepackage{mathrsfs}\usepackage{pifont}\usepackage{stmaryrd}\usepackage{textcomp}\usepackage{portland, xspace}\usepackage{amsmath, amsxtra}\usepackage{upgreek}\pagestyle{empty}\DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}\begin{document}
$$\kappa =$$
\end{document} 0.2.

The learning algorithm is guided by a prior that captures the idea that the highest performing gaits are likely to be a combination of motors at full speed (in forward or in reverse). In our implementation, it is implemented with a Gaussian process defined by nine hand-picked points and whose variance is ignored (Eq. 2). The kernel function is the exponential kernel (Eq. 3), with \documentclass{aastex}\usepackage{amsbsy}\usepackage{amsfonts}\usepackage{amssymb}\usepackage{bm}\usepackage{mathrsfs}\usepackage{pifont}\usepackage{stmaryrd}\usepackage{textcomp}\usepackage{portland, xspace}\usepackage{amsmath, amsxtra}\usepackage{upgreek}\pagestyle{empty}\DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}\begin{document}
$$\beta = 0.15$$
\end{document}.

The nine hand-picked points (\documentclass{aastex}\usepackage{amsbsy}\usepackage{amsfonts}\usepackage{amssymb}\usepackage{bm}\usepackage{mathrsfs}\usepackage{pifont}\usepackage{stmaryrd}\usepackage{textcomp}\usepackage{portland, xspace}\usepackage{amsmath, amsxtra}\usepackage{upgreek}\pagestyle{empty}\DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}\begin{document}
$${ \chi _{ \bf{1}}} , \cdots , { \chi _{ \bf{9}}}$$
\end{document}) are as follows (Fig. 2D):
